<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="31" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1082,2004]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,325,1269,1295]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[333,570,1269,1294]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Microdytes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="whitingi">
<emphasis box="[333,570,1269,1294]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">Microdytes whitingi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[705,856,1269,1295]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Microdytes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cameroni">
<emphasis box="[705,729,1269,1294]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[745,856,1269,1294]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">cameroni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[915,1044,1269,1295]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Microdytes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boukali">
<emphasis box="[915,939,1269,1294]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[955,1044,1269,1294]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">boukali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the very fine to almost absent punctation on dorsal and ventral surfaces, but differs from them in having the body overall oblong-oval and dorsoventrally compressed and the predominantly yellow-brown elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="32" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1082,2004]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,355,1381,1407]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[364,541,1381,1406]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">Measurements</emphasis>
. TL = 
<quantity box="[628,809,1381,1407]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.43" metricValueMax="1.53" metricValueMin="1.33" pageId="5" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="1.43" valueMax="1.53" valueMin="1.33">1.33–1.53 mm</quantity>
, GW = 0.83–1.00 mm, TL/GW = 1.54–1.59. Body dorsoventrally compressed and flattened; lateral outline continuous between pronotum and elytron; lateral margins of elytron relatively parallel-sided (
<figureCitation box="[667,738,1456,1482]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,269,868,892]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,318,827]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,306,847]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Dorsal habitus and variations of color patterns of Microdytes species: 1) M. svensoni; 2) M. cameroni; 3) M. whitingi; 4) M. sabitae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/204747/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1082,2004]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis box="[198,327,1493,1518]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">Coloration</emphasis>
. Head yellow-brown, darker along the eyes. Pronotum red-brown to dark brown, yellowbrown along lateral margins. Elytron predominantly yellow-brown, dark brown along base and suture and with diffuse light-brown maculae (
<figureCitation box="[562,635,1568,1594]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,269,868,892]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,318,827]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,306,847]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Dorsal habitus and variations of color patterns of Microdytes species: 1) M. svensoni; 2) M. cameroni; 3) M. whitingi; 4) M. sabitae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/204747/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Ventral surfaces of head, prothorax and posterior three abdominal ventrites yellowish; thorax, anterior two abdominal ventrites and elytral epipleuron red-brown; legs, antennae and palpi yellowish-brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1082,2004]" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis box="[198,478,1680,1705]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="31">Sculpture and structure</emphasis>
. Head with very fine, inconspicuous, irregular punctation; other microsculpture indistinct; clypeus evenly rounded, anterior clypeal margin flattened and extended anteriorly but without distinct subapical depression or marginal bead; eyes small. Pronotum with very fine, inconspicuous, irregular punctation or with punctation almost absent; other microsculpture absent; with posterior angles not produced posteriorly; lateral bead distinct and of even width throughout. Elytron with very fine, irregular punctation or with punctation almost absent, with discal series of punctures more pronounced posteriorly; dorsolateral series of punctures present anteriorly; other microsculpture absent. Metaventrite, metacoxae and abdominal ventrites with very fine, irregular punctation or with punctation almost absent; ventral side without other microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,152,439]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis box="[198,370,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">Male genitalia</emphasis>
. Median lobe in ventral aspect (
<figureCitation box="[748,819,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1483,1507]" captionTargetBox="[406,1163,188,1423]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[391,1195,173,1463]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 8. Median lobe of aedeagus: a) dorsal aspect, b) right lateral aspect: 5) M. svensoni; 6) M. cameroni; 7) M. whitingi; 8) M. sabitae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/204748/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
a), in lateral aspect (
<figureCitation box="[1055,1126,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1483,1507]" captionTargetBox="[406,1163,188,1423]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[391,1195,173,1463]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 8. Median lobe of aedeagus: a) dorsal aspect, b) right lateral aspect: 5) M. svensoni; 6) M. cameroni; 7) M. whitingi; 8) M. sabitae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/204748/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
b). Lateral lobes in ventral aspect fused apically (
<figureCitation box="[410,499,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1897,1921]" captionTargetBox="[280,1292,400,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[268,1318,381,1876]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Lateral lobes of aedeagus: a) dorsal aspect, b) lateral aspect: 9) M. svensoni; 10) M. cameroni; 11) M. whitingi; 12) M. sabitae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/204749/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">Figs 11</figureCitation>
a), lateral aspect (
<figureCitation box="[705,789,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,270,1897,1921]" captionTargetBox="[280,1292,400,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[268,1318,381,1876]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Lateral lobes of aedeagus: a) dorsal aspect, b) lateral aspect: 9) M. svensoni; 10) M. cameroni; 11) M. whitingi; 12) M. sabitae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/204749/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
b).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,152,439]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis box="[196,308,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">Variation</emphasis>
. This species varies somewhat in the extent of the elytral maculae and the depth of brown coloration.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="32" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,152,439]" box="[196,1363,301,327]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,337,301,327]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named in honor of esteemed colleague, M.F. Whiting, Provo, UT, 
<collectingCountry box="[1297,1360,301,327]" name="United States of America" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">USA</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,152,439]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,301,338,364]" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">Habitat.</emphasis>
The species was found in a small, torrential stream in the 
<collectingRegion box="[1005,1102,338,364]" country="American Samoa" name="Western" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">Western</collectingRegion>
Ghats area of southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[151,215,376,402]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">India</collectingCountry>
. It was found in the same locality and habitat as 
<taxonomicName box="[784,907,376,401]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Microdytes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sabitae">
<emphasis box="[784,907,376,401]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="32">M. sabitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
